## 5. Chapter Splitting Strategies

### 5.1 Timestamp-Based Splitting (Preferred)

```python
# Input: chapter_guide from YouTube description
# Format: "0:00 Introduction\n2:15 First Topic\n5:30 Second Topic"

_parse_chapter_guide(guide)  # → [(0, "Introduction"), (135, "First Topic"), (330, "Second Topic")]
```

Maps each timestamp → finds nearest [(mm:ss)](file:///F:/1.%20Edit%20Videos/8.AntiCode/2.Script_Split_Chapter/ui/rewrite_style_tab.py#1065-1067) timecode in transcript text → splits at that position. Adjusts boundary to the nearest sentence start (`. ` or `? ` or `! `).

### 5.2 AI Marker-Based Splitting (Fallback)

```
1. Send transcript text + system prompt to AI
2. AI identifies "start markers" — distinctive phrases marking chapter boundaries
3. Parse AI response (JSON with markers array)
4. Find each marker in original text
5. Adjust each boundary to nearest sentence start
6. Generate Chapter objects with auto-numbered titles
```

> [!NOTE]
> Both strategies use `_adjust_to_sentence_boundary()` — shifts the split point backwards to the first sentence-ending punctuation (`. `, `? `, `! `) to avoid mid-sentence breaks.

