## 6. Checkpoint & Resume System

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    subgraph Checkpoint Steps
        S1["STEP_SPLIT"] --> S2["STEP_VERIFY"]
        S2 --> S3["STEP_PUNCTUATE"]
        S3 --> S4["STEP_DONE"]
    end
```

| Function | Purpose |
|----------|---------|
| [save_checkpoint(output_dir, step, chapters)](file:///F:/1.%20Edit%20Videos/8.AntiCode/2.Script_Split_Chapter/core/chapter_splitter.py#52-65) | Saves `_checkpoint.json` with step + serialized chapters |
| [load_checkpoint(output_dir)](file:///F:/1.%20Edit%20Videos/8.AntiCode/2.Script_Split_Chapter/core/chapter_splitter.py#67-79) | Returns [(step, chapters)](file:///F:/1.%20Edit%20Videos/8.AntiCode/2.Script_Split_Chapter/ui/rewrite_style_tab.py#1065-1067) or `None` |
| [delete_checkpoint(output_dir)](file:///F:/1.%20Edit%20Videos/8.AntiCode/2.Script_Split_Chapter/core/chapter_splitter.py#81-89) | Removes checkpoint on success |

**Resume logic:** When processing starts, if a checkpoint exists in the output directory, the pipeline skips already-completed steps and resumes from the saved step. This enables crash recovery for long-running batch jobs.

